# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aboriginal-whaling
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aboriginal-whaling/aboriginal-whaling] Under the terms of the 1986 moratorium, the International Whaling Commission allows the activity to be carried out by aboriginal groups if it occurs on a subsistence basis, similar to subsistence fishing.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/aboriginal-whaling] This **Aboriginal Subsistence Whaling** is restricted to native peoples and others working on their behalf, as defined by the IWC.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/aboriginal-whaling] Since its inception, the IWC has recognised that indigenous or 'aboriginal subsistence' whaling is of a different nature to commercial whaling.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/aboriginal-whaling] It is thus not subject to the moratorium.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/aboriginal-whaling] This is reflected in the different objectives for the two types of whaling.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/aboriginal-whaling] In order for a country to carry out a hunt under the aboriginal group clause, the nation must provide the IWC with evidence of "the cultural and subsistence needs of their people." In particular, the hunt is not intended for commercial purposes and the caught meat cannot be exported.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/aboriginal-whaling] In 2018, the Commission endorsed proposals made by a working group established six-years earlier to consider some long-standing and complex questions, and improve the way that the Commission considered ASW.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/aboriginal-whaling] A number of new initiatives were endorsed in order to facilitate a more straight-forward process when catch limits are next considered at the 2024 meeting of the Commission.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/aboriginal-whaling] In the United States whaling is carried out by Alaska Natives and by the Makah of Washington State.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/aboriginal-whaling] It no longer occurs on the Atlantic coast, although the Pilgrim Fathers found the original inhabitants of New England had a well-developed understanding of drift whales.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/aboriginal-whaling] The Arctic whaling program is managed by the Alaska Eskimo Whaling Commission, which reports to the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/aboriginal-whaling] The commission includes eleven whaling communities which inhabit the Arctic Alaska coast: the Gambell, Savoonga, Wales, Little Diomede, Kivalina, Point Hope, Point Lay, Wainwright, Barrow, Nuiqsut, and Kaktovik.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/aboriginal-whaling] In 2015 Alaska Natives caught 326 beluga whales and 49 bowhead whales.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/aboriginal-whaling] In 2016 they caught 59 bowhead whales, two minke and one humpback whale; The latter two species were not authorized, though no one was prosecuted.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/aboriginal-whaling] Annual catches vary between 300 and 500 belugas and 40 to 70 bowheads.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/aboriginal-whaling] The hunt takes the bowhead whales from a population of about 10,000 in Alaskan waters.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/aboriginal-whaling] Anti-whaling groups claim this hunt is not sustainable, though the IWC Scientific Committee, the same group that provided the above population estimate, projects a population growth of 3.2% per year.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/aboriginal-whaling] The hunt also took an average of one or two gray whales each year until 1996.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/aboriginal-whaling] The quota was reduced to zero in that year due to concerns about sustainability.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/aboriginal-whaling] According to federal law, the Makah people of Washington State are entitled to hunt and kill one baleen whale, typically a gray whale, each year, though archeological records and oral history indicate a significant number of humpback whales were hunted as well.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/aboriginal-whaling] The Makah ended their whaling practices in the 1920s, but notified the U.S.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/aboriginal-whaling] Government of their wish to reassert their whaling rights in 1995.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/aboriginal-whaling] The first permitted Makah whale hunt in 70 years occurred on 17 May 1999, when they caught a north Pacific gray whale, an unpermitted hunt killed another in 2007, and in 2018 they took meat from a humpback killed by a ship strike.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/aboriginal-whaling] An environmental impact statement for further hunts was issued in 2015.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/aboriginal-whaling] On 5 April 2019 NOAA Fisheries proposed issuing a waiver under the MMPA to the Makah tribe to allow hunting, as well as a what stakeholders can do to engage in the public rule making process before an Administrative Law Judge.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/aboriginal-whaling] One of the main stipulations that NOAA proposed was allowing the Makah people to hunt as many as 20 gray whales every five years, however prior to any hunt the tribe would have to obtain a permit from NOAA.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/aboriginal-whaling] On 2 August 2019 the Administrative Law Judge announced that the final agenda for the hearing on NOAA's proposed waiver and regulations was set for November 2019, which was postponed from the previous 26 June 2019 announcement.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/aboriginal-whaling] Canada left the IWC in 1982 and as such is not bound by the moratorium.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/aboriginal-whaling] Whaling is carried out by various Inuit groups in the Canadian Arctic in small numbers and is managed by the Department of Fisheries and Oceans.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/aboriginal-whaling] Chukchi people of the Chukotka Autonomous Okrug in the Russian Far East are permitted to take up to 140 gray whales from the North-East Pacific population and 67 Bering-Chukchi-Beaufort bowhead whales in the period 2026 - 2031.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/aboriginal-whaling] Some whaling is conducted from Grenada, Dominica, Saint Vincent and the Grenadines and Saint Lucia.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/aboriginal-whaling] Species hunted are the short-finned pilot whale, killer whale, pygmy killer whale and spinner dolphins.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/aboriginal-whaling] Throughout the Caribbean, around 400 pilot whales are killed annually with the meat being sold locally.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/aboriginal-whaling] This hunting of small cetaceans is not regulated by the IWC.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/aboriginal-whaling] Whales are hunted in Bequia, the largest of the Grenadines.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/aboriginal-whaling] Natives of Bequia are allowed to catch up to four humpback whales per year using only traditional hunting methods of hand-thrown harpoons in small, open sailboats.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/aboriginal-whaling] The limit is rarely met, with no catch some years.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/aboriginal-whaling] Its classification as aboriginal, and therefore permissible, is highly contested.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/aboriginal-whaling] In the 2012 meeting of the IWC, delegates from several anti-whaling countries, and environmental groups, spoke out against it, with Peter Sanchez of the Dominican Republic calling it "artisanal whaling out of control".
[src:aboriginal-whaling/aboriginal-whaling] Whalers in the Faroe Islands take approximately 800 long-finned pilot whales per year.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/aboriginal-whaling] These hunts are called *grindadráp* in Faroese.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/aboriginal-whaling] Lamalera, on the south coast of the island of Lembata, and Lamakera on neighbouring Solor are the last two remaining Indonesian whaling communities.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/aboriginal-whaling] The hunters have religious taboos that ensure that they use every part of the animal.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/aboriginal-whaling] About half of the catch is kept in the village; the rest is traded in local markets, using barter.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/aboriginal-whaling] The whale hunts are carried out in a traditional manner, with bamboo spears and small wooden outriggers, 10–12 m long and 2m wide, constructed without nails and with sails woven from palm fronds.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/aboriginal-whaling] The animals are killed by the harpooner leaping onto the back of the animal, from the boat, to drive in the harpoon.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/aboriginal-whaling] The people of Lamalera hunt several species of whales, primarily sperm whales (the baleen whale is taboo), and in the peak year of 1969 caught 56 sperm whales.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/aboriginal-whaling] In addition to whales, dolphins, manta rays, turtles and several species of sharks are also hunted.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/aboriginal-whaling] In 1973, the United Nations Food and Agriculture Organization sent a whaling ship and a Norwegian master whaler, to modernize the hunt.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/aboriginal-whaling] This effort lasted three years, and was not successful.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/aboriginal-whaling] The World Wildlife Fund has carried out surveys in the village to determine that the limited hunting does not endanger world whale stocks or other endangered species.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/aboriginal-whaling] Commercial whaling and poachers hunt whales in large quantities and sell them illegally.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/aboriginal-whaling] The International Whaling Commission (IWC) does not allow the hunting of any whales except for aboriginal subsistence whaling and scientific whaling, which have catch limits to maintain the conservation of whales.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/aboriginal-whaling] These groups must report their hunts and the number of whales killed in order to track the population of whale species and conservation.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/aboriginal-whaling] Hunting illegally means the kills are not reported, which makes it difficult to maintain population numbers and conservation.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] An **air gun** or **airgun** is a gun that uses compressed air or other pressurized gases to fire projectiles, reminiscent of the principle behind the ancient blowgun.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] This is in contrast to a firearm, which shoots projectiles using pressure generated via combustion of a chemical propellant, most often black powder in antique firearms and smokeless powder in modern firearms.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Air guns come in both long gun (**air rifle**) and handgun (**air pistol**) forms.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Both types typically propel metallic projectiles that are either diabolo-shaped pellets or spherical shots called BBs, although in recent years Minié ball-shaped cylindro-conoidal projectiles called slugs are becoming more popular.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Certain types of air guns (usually air rifles) may also launch fin-stabilized projectile such as darts (e.g., tranquilizer guns) or hollow-shafted arrows (so-called "airbows").
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] The air guns were first developed in the 16th century, and have since been used in hunting, shooting sports, and even in warfare.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] There are three different power sources for modern air guns, depending on the design: spring-piston, pneumatic or bottled compressed gas (most commonly carbon dioxide and recently nitrogen).
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Air guns represent the oldest pneumatic technology.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] The oldest existing mechanical air gun dates back to about 1580, and is currently kept in the Livrustkammaren Museum in Stockholm.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] This is approximately what most historians recognize as the beginning of the modern air gun.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Throughout 17th to 19th century, air guns in .30 to .51 calibers were used to hunt big game, deer and wild boar.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] These air rifles were charged using a pump to fill an air reservoir and produced velocities from 650 to 1,000 ft/s (200 to 300 m/s).
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] They were also used in warfare, the most recognized example being the Girandoni air rifle, a repeating rifle used by Austria in the 1788 war against Turkey.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] At that time, they had compelling advantages over the muzzleloader firearms of the day.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] For example, air guns could be discharged in wet weather and rain (unlike both matchlock and flintlock muskets), and discharged much faster than muzzle-loading guns.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Moreover, they were quieter than a firearm of a similar caliber and produced no muzzle flash or smoke cloud when fired.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Thus, they did not give away the shooter's position or obscure the shooter's view, unlike the black powder muskets of the 18th and 19th centuries.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] In the hands of skilled soldiers, they gave the military a distinct advantage.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] France, Austria and other nations had special sniper detachments using air rifles, mostly Jäger (infantry).
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] The Austrian 1779 model was named *Windbüchse* (literally "wind rifle" in German).
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] The gun was developed in 1768 or 1769 by the Tyrolean Ladins watchmaker, mechanic and gunsmith Bartholomäus Girardoni (1744–1799) and is sometimes referred to as the Girandoni air rifle or Girardoni air gun in literature (the name is also spelled "Girandony", "Giradoni" or "Girardoni".).
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Adopted by the Austrian leadership in 1779, the *Windbüchse* was about 4 ft (1.2 m) long and weighed 10 pounds (4.5 kg), about the same size and mass as a conventional musket.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] The air reservoir was a removable, club-shaped, butt.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] The *Windbüchse* carried twenty-two .51 caliber (13 mm) lead balls in a tubular magazine.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] A skilled shooter could fire off one magazine in about thirty seconds.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] A shot from this air gun could penetrate a one-inch-thick (2.5 cm) wooden board at a hundred paces, an effect roughly equal to that of a modern 9×19mm or .45 ACP caliber pistol.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Circa 1820, the Japanese inventor Kunitomo Ikkansai developed various manufacturing methods for guns, and also created an air gun based on the study of Western knowledge ("rangaku") acquired from the Dutch in Dejima.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] The Lewis and Clark Expedition (1804) carried a reservoir air gun, very likely the Girardoni, as it held 22 round balls of .46 caliber in a tubular magazine mounted on the side of the barrel.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] The butt of the gun served as the air reservoir and had a working pressure of 800 psi (55 bar).
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] The rifle was said to be capable of 22 aimed shots per minute and had a rifled bore of 0.452 in (11.5 mm) and a groove diameter 0.462 in (11.7 mm).
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] One of the first commercially successful and mass-produced air guns was manufactured by the William F.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Markham's Markham Air Rifle Company in Plymouth, Michigan, US.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Their first model air gun was the wooden *Challenger*, marketed in 1886.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] In response, Clarence Hamilton from the neighboring Plymouth Air Rifle Company (later renamed to Daisy Manufacturing Company in 1895) marketed their all-metal Daisy BB Gun in early 1888, which prompted Markham to respond with their *Chicago* model in 1888 followed by the *King* model in 1890.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] The *Chicago* model was sold by Sears, Roebuck for 73 cents in its catalog.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] In 1928, the name of the Markham company was changed to King Air Rifle Company after the company was purchased by Daisy in 1916 after decades of intense competition, and continued to manufacture the "King" model air rifle until 1935 before ceasing operation altogether in the 1940s.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] From the 1890s onwards, air rifles were used in Birmingham, England for competitive target shooting.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Matches were held in public houses and working men's clubs, which sponsored shooting teams.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] This often took the form of Bell Target shooting, where the competitor aims to ring a bell by shooting through a small hole in a steel plate.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Prizes, such as a leg of mutton for the winning team, were paid for by the losing team.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] During this time, over 4,000 air rifle clubs and associations existed across Great Britain, with as many as 1,600 in Birmingham alone.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] During this time, the air gun was associated with poaching because it could deliver a shot without a significant muzzle report.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Air guns are used for hunting (small to medium game), pest control, recreational shooting (commonly known as plinking) and competitive sports such as the Olympic 10 m air rifle and 10 m air pistol events.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Field target (FT) is a competitive form of metallic silhouette shooting in which the targets are animal-shaped steel targets with a "kill zone" cut-out.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Hunter field target (HFT) is a variation, using identical equipment, but with differing rules.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] The distances FT and HFT competitions are shot at range between 7.3 and 41.1 metres (24 and 135 ft) for HFT & 7.3 and 50.29 metres (24.0 and 165.0 ft) for FT, with varying sizes of "reducers" being used to increase or decrease the size of the kill zone.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] In the UK, competition power limits are set at the legal maximum for an unlicensed air rifle, i.e.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Air rifle benchrest is an international shooting sport where the objective is to hit a (small) bulls eye target at 25 m (27.34 yd) shooting distance.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] There are two divisions ARLV 12 ft⋅lbf (16.27 J) and ARHV 20 ft⋅lbf (27.12 J).
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] The increasing affordability of higher-power pre-charged pneumatic (PCP) rifles has allowed large projectiles and further target distance for competition purposes.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] For instance, the Extreme Benchrest competition held annually in Green Valley, Arizona allows calibers up to .30 inches (7.6 mm) at 75 yd (68.58 m) while the Big Bore Benchrest arm of the same competition at other localities engages targets at 35 to 300 yards (32 to 274 m).
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] The component of an airgun that provides the gas pressure needed to propel projectiles is called its *powerplant*, which uses internally stored pressurized gas; and *compressed gas* (most commonly CO2), which uses external sources of pressurized gas.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] A **spring-piston air gun** (also known as a **spring gun** or simply a "**springer**") operates by means of a spring-loaded piston pump assembly contained within a compression chamber separate from the gun barrel.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Traditionally, a grease-lubricated steel coil spring is used as the powerplant main spring.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Before shooting, the user needs to manually cock the gun by flexing a lever connected to the pump assembly, which pulls the pump piston rearwards and compresses the main spring until the rear of the piston engages the sear.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] When shooting, the trigger is pulled and disengages the sear, allowing the main spring to decompress and release its stored elastic potential energy, pushing the piston forward, thereby compressing the air in the pump cylinder.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] All this takes place in a fraction of a second, during which the air undergoes adiabatic heating to several hundred degrees and then cools as the air expands.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] This can also cause a phenomenon referred as "dieseling", where flammable substances in the compression chamber (e.g., petroleum-based lubricant) can be ignited by the compression heat like in a diesel engine, and lead to an afterburner effect with (often unpredictable) additional thrusts.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] This often results in combustion smoke coming out of the muzzle and potential pressure damage to the rubber O-ring seals inside the gun.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Dieseling can be made to occur *intentionally* to increase power, by coating the pellet with lubricant or petroleum jelly, although this may result in damage to the breech seal.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Most spring-piston guns are single-shot breechloaders by nature, but multiple-shot repeaters with magazine feeders have been introduced in recent years by manufacturers such as Gamo, Umarex and Hatsan.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Spring-piston guns, especially the high-powered "magnum" guns, are able to achieve muzzle velocities exceeding the speed of sound.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] The effort required for the cocking stroke is proportional to the designed power of the gun, with higher muzzle velocities requiring a stiffer spring and hence a greater cocking effort.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Spring-piston guns have a practical upper limit of 1,250 ft/s (380 m/s) for .177 cal (4.5 mm) pellets, as higher velocities cause unstable pellet flight and loss of accuracy.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] This is due to the extreme buffeting caused when the pellet reaches and surpasses transonic speed, then slows back down and goes through sound barrier again, which is more than enough to destabilize the pellet's flight.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Shortly after leaving the barrel, the supersonic pellet falls back below the speed of sound and the shock wave overtakes the pellet, causing its flight stability to be disrupted.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Drag increases disproportionately as pellet velocity increases, so it is generally better to increase pellet weight to keep velocities subsonic in high-powered guns.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Many shooters find that velocities in the 800–900 ft/s (240–270 m/s) range offer an ideal balance between power and accuracy.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Spring-piston guns, especially high-powered ("magnum") models, do still recoil as a result of the mainspring pushing the piston forward.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Although the recoil is less than that of some cartridge firearms, it can make the gun difficult to shoot accurately as the spring recoil is in effect while the pellet is still within the barrel.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Spring gun recoil also has a sharp forward component, caused by the piston hitting the front end of the pump chamber when the spring has fully decompressed.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] These rapid double-jerking movements are known to damage scopes not rated for spring gun usage.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] In addition, the spring often has unpredictable collateral transverse vibrations as well as torquing, both of which can cause accuracy to suffer.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] The better quality spring guns can have very long service lives, being simple to maintain and repair.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Because they deliver the same mechanical energy output on each shot, external ballistics are quite consistent.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Most Olympic air gun competitions through the 1970s and into the 1980s were shot with spring-piston guns, often of the opposing-piston recoil-eliminating type.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Beginning in the 1980s, guns powered by compressed/liquefied carbon dioxide began to dominate the competition.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Today, the guns used at the highest levels of competition are powered by compressed air.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Some newer generation air guns incorporate a gas spring (commonly referred to as a *gas piston*, *gas ram*, *gas strut* or *nitro piston*) instead of a mechanical spring.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] The spring itself is essentially a stand-alone enclosed piston pump without outlets and with pressurized air or inert gas (such as nitrogen) held tightly sealed within the cylinder.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] When the gun is cocked, the gas inside the cylinder gets further compressed by the piston, stores potential energy and acts as a pneumatic accumulator.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Gas spring units require higher precision to manufacture since they require a low-friction sliding seal that can withstand the high pressures within when cocked.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Gas springs perform more reliably in cold climates than coil springs, because metallic coil springs need to be coated with lubricating grease which often thickens in low temperatures causing the gun to "freeze up".
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Gas springs also have less lateral and longitudinal vibrations than coil springs, hence are usually less "hold-sensitive", making it easier to achieve consistent shot groupings.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Pneumatic airguns propel the projectiles by utilizing the pneumatic potential energy within compressed air, which is pressurized beforehand and stored inside the gun, and then released through valves during shooting.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Single-stroke and multi-stroke pump guns utilize an on-board hand pump to pressurize air in an internal reservoir tank, while pre-charged pneumatic guns' reservoirs are filled from an external source using either a high-pressure stand pump or by decanting air from a larger diving cylinder.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Because of the need for cylinders or charging systems, PCP guns have higher initial costs but much lower operating costs when compared to CO2 rifles, and have superior performance over ordinary pump guns.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Having no significant movement of heavy mechanical parts during the discharge cycle, PCP airgun designs produce lower recoil, and can shoot as many as 100 shots per charge depending on the tank/reservoir size.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] The ready supply of air has allowed the development of semi- and fully automatic air guns.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] PCP guns are very popular in Europe because of their accuracy and ease of use.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] They are widely utilized in ISSF 10 meter air pistol and rifle shooting events and the sport of Field Target shooting, and are usually fitted with telescopic sights.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Early stand pump designs encountered problems of fatigue (both human and mechanical), temperature warping, and condensation – none of which are beneficial to accurate shooting or the airguns' longevity.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Modern stand pumps have multi-stage chambers and built-in air filtration systems and have overcome many of these problems.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Using scuba-quality air decanted from a diving cylinder provides consistently clean, dry, high-pressure air.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] During the typical PCP's discharge cycle, the hammer of the rifle is released by the sear to strike the bash valve.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] The hammer may move rearwards or forwards, unlike firearms where the hammer almost always moves forward.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] The valve is held closed by a spring and the pressure of the air in the reservoir.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] The pressure of the spring is constant, and the pressure of the air released (which is also known as the *working pressure*) decreases with each successive shot.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] As a result, when the reservoir pressure is high, the valve opens less fully and closes faster than when the reservoir pressure is lower, resulting in a similar total volume of air flowing past the valve with each shot.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] This results in a degree of partial self-regulation that gives a greater consistency of velocity from shot to shot, which corresponds to the middle "plateau" phase of the gun's shot-to-shot muzzle velocity profile (also known as the *power curve* ).
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Well-designed PCP will display good shot-to-shot consistency over a long period, as the air reservoir is being depleted.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Other PCP rifles and pistols are regulated, i.e. the firing valve operates within a secondary chamber separated from the main air reservoir by the regulator body.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] The regulator maintains the pressure within this secondary chamber at a set pressure (lower than the main reservoir's) until the main reservoir's pressure drops to the point where it can no longer do so.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] As a result, shot-to-shot consistency is maintained for longer than in an unregulated rifle, and the gun can also output more shots due to reduced waste of reservoir pressure.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] CO2 guns are popular for training, as the guns and ammunition are inexpensive, relatively safe to use, and no specialized facilities are needed for safety.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] In addition, they can be purchased and owned in areas where firearms possession is either strictly controlled or banned outright.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Most CO2 powered guns are relatively inexpensive, and there are a few precision target guns available that use CO2.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] The high-pressure air (HPA) system, or *N2*, was originally developed for paintball markers as a replacement for CO2 cartridges, and uses powerlet interface-compatible diving cylinders filled with either pure nitrogen or compressed air (which is 78% nitrogen).
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Because nitrogen is more inert than CO2, it remains in the gaseous state longer when compressed; when it expands, it cools due to the Joule-Thomson effect, but at a far lower rate than liquid CO2 because there is no change in state from liquid to gas.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] This thermostability reduces the variation in output pressure associated with rapid successions of firing cycles, improving accuracy and reliability in extreme climates.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] However, because compressed air is stored at higher pressures (up to 34 MPa or 4,900 psi) than liquid CO2 (stored at around 8 MPa or 1,200 psi), HPA cylinders are more expensive.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Cylinders smaller than 1.1 L (67 cu in) may not even last as long as a standard CO2 cartridge when subjected to frequent use.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] It is also possible to power an HPA-compatible gun directly from a plug-in air compressor without using a gas cylinder, though this type of setup is rare.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Each air cartridge is essentially a self-contained gas reservoir housed inside a cartridge case (usually in the size of a .38 Special), with an internal bash valve designed to release the content when the base of the cartridge is struck.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Prior to shooting, each cartridge is pre-filled with sufficient compressed air for one shot (typically via a multi-stroke hand pump) and has a .177/.22 caliber pellet pre-seated to its front slot, and the entire cartridge is then inserted into a chamber in the gun barrel.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] When shooting, the hammer hits the rear of the air cartridge, mimicking the function of a centerfire ammunition.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] This allows the airgun to be constructed and operated in similar fashions to genuine firearms.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] It also allows for higher shot consistency because each cartridge can be easily filled to an identical air charge, essentially removing the "power curve" of conventional PCP guns and bypassing any need for regulators.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] It also simplifies the magazine feed design and eliminates the risk of deforming the projectiles when the action seats each pellet, as the soft lead pellet is protected from contact with the action probe by the harder cartridge casing.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] The air cartridge system, both in the rifle and revolver forms, was at the peak of its popularity throughout the 1990s.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] The popularity of the Brocock range was such that, by 2002, estimates put the number of air cartridge guns in circulation around 70,000-80,000.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] However, a small number of incidents relating to the alleged illegal conversion of (mainly) Brococks to allow them to discharge live ammunition sparked a media frenzy.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] After the UK government implemented the Anti-social Behaviour Act 2003 in January 2004, it became illegal to possess such airguns without a firearm certificate in the United Kingdom.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Brocock subsequently ceased production of all air cartridge systems and turned to focus primarily on PCP airguns.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] The most popular ammunition used in rifled air guns is made of lead, a heavy metal.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Lead is highly poisonous (whether inhaled or swallowed), affecting almost every organ and system in the human body.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] For this reason, lead-free pellets are becoming increasingly popular, and are available in all major shapes and styles, just like traditional lead pellets.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] In flight, the skirt has greater drag-to-weight ratio than the head and exerts a rearward pull behind the center of mass, similar to that of a shuttlecock.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] This produces a phenomenon known as *drag stabilization*, which helps to counteract yawing and maintain a consistent flight path.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] However, the diabolo shape also means that the overall pellet will have poor ballistic coefficient and tends to lose energy quickly and be more unstable especially in the transonic region (272–408 m/s ~ 893–1340 ft/s).
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Diabolo pellets are conventionally made from lead, but are widely available in non-lead alternatives, such as tin, or a combination of materials such as steel or gold alloys with polymer tips.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] A variety of lead-free pellets are offered by all major pellet manufacturers, including H&N Sport, RWS, JSB, Gamo, and others.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Since lead is very dense, it has a higher ballistic coefficient than lightweight alternatives such as tin, copper, or plastic.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] At the present time, the airgun industry does not mass-produce dense alternatives to lead with a high ballistic coefficient for long-range shooting.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Some manufacturers also have recently introduced the more cylindro-conoidal-shaped "slug" pellets for the more powerful modern PCP air rifles.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Appropriately sized bullets cast from firearm bullet molds can be used in big bore air rifles.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Caution should be used when handling lead projectiles or preparing animals for food, as lead fragments can be easily missed inside the meat.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Lead-free slugs in airgun calibers are gradually being developed and becoming available for purchase from manufacturers such as Zan Projectiles, due in part to regulations on hunting with lead projectiles in many areas.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] The BB shot was once the most common airgun ammunition in the US, thanks to the popularity of Daisy's line of BB airguns.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] A BB is a small metallic ball in 4.5 mm/.177" diameter, typically made of steel (with a copper or zinc coating) or lead.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Originally called the "round shot", the contemporary name came from the "BB"- size lead birdshot used in shotgun shells, which the first BB gun invented in 1886 was designed to shoot.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Steel BBs can be acceptably accurate at short distances when fired from properly designed BB guns with smoothbore barrels.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Lead #3 buckshot pellets can be used in .25" caliber airguns as if they were large BBs.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Therefore, steel BBs lack the spin stabilization required for long-range accuracy, and usage in any but the cheapest rifled guns is discouraged.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] The softer lead BBs, however, can be used in rifled barrels.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Typically BBs are used for indoor practice, casual outdoor plinking, training children, or to save money, as they are significantly cheaper than pellets.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Replica CO2 pistols allow people to train with a BB gun, saving a lot of money to centerfire firearm cartridges.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Care should be exercised to avoid ricochet, and safety glasses are recommended.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Recently, manufacturers have created frangible BBs, which break apart and do not ricochet, reducing the hazards associated with BB guns.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Some shotgunners use sightless BB rifles to train in instinctive shooting.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Similar guns were also used briefly by the United States Army in a Vietnam-era instinctive shooting program called "Quick Kill".
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] In the 18th and 19th centuries, air gun darts were popular, largely because they could be reused.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Although less popular now, several different types of darts are made to be used in air guns, but it is not recommended that darts be used in air guns with rifled bores or in spring-powered air guns.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Air guns that shoot darts are sometimes called *dart guns*, and *tranquilizer guns* if the darts used are loaded with anesthetic (tranquilizer) compounds.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Some modern air guns are designed to discharge arrows and are called *arrow guns* or sometimes *airbows*.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] These arrows are designed with a hollow shaft that is open in the rear where the nock would normally be.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] When loaded, the hollow arrow shaft is slid rearwards over a barrel whose external diameter is only fractionally smaller than the shaft's interior diameter, providing a close-enough fitting that minimizes rattling and gives a reasonable enveloping seal without causing too much friction.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] During shooting, the trigger releases high-pressure air from the barrel to the front portion of the hollow arrow shaft, pushing the arrow forward.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Such air guns can shoot arrows at launch velocities rivalling or even exceeding high-end crossbows, while retaining consistency of precision unaffected by archer's paradox, but they are also more expensive to set up and maintain.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] The modern pentathlon has since 2009 included a laser-run event that replaced the traditional cross country run of 3,200 metres and timed air-pistol shoot.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] The competitors run 4 laps of 800 m combined with 4 rounds of firing.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] The pistols used are modified air pistols that fire an eye-safe laser beam towards a target at the same time as a discharge of air.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] This has made the organisation of the events easier from a safety point of view and allows competitors to travel more easily with their weapons.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Airsoft pellets are plastic BBs shot from airsoft guns.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Larger caliber air rifles suitable for hunting large animals are offered by major manufacturers.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Custom air guns are available in even larger calibers such as 20 mm (0.79") or .87 (22.1 mm).
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] While in some countries air guns are not subject to any specific regulation, in most, there are laws which differ widely.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Each jurisdiction has its definition of an air gun.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Regulations may vary for weapons of different bore, muzzle energy, velocity, or ammunition material.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Guns designed to fire metal pellets are often more tightly controlled than airsoft weapons.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] There may be a minimum age for possession, and sales of both air guns and ammunition may be restricted.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] Some areas require permits and background checks similar to those required for propellant type firearms.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] While historical air guns have been made specifically for warfare, modern air guns can also be deadly.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] In medical literature, modern air guns have been noted as a cause of death.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] This has been the case for guns of caliber .177 and .22 that are within the legal muzzle energy of air guns in the United Kingdom.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/air-gun] For reason of safety and security a rule of use of the safety flag has been strictly mentioned by ISSF for the 10m air pistol and rifle shooting sports events.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] The migration of Alaska Natives' ancestors into the Alaskan region occurred thousands of years ago in multiple waves.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] Some present-day groups descend from a later migration event whose descendants gradually settled across northern North America.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] The Alaska Native's ancestors are the ones who did not migrate further south or east.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] Genetic evidence indicates that these groups are not closely related to the Indigenous peoples of South America.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] Evidence from archaeology indicates that the ancestors of Alaska Natives migrated from Asia.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] Anthropologists have proposed that their journey to Alaska from Asia was made possible through the Bering land bridge or by traveling across the sea.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] Across the Arctic and the circumpolar north, the ancestors of Alaska Natives established a variety of Indigenous cultures that developed and changed over time.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] These cultures demonstrated considerable ingenuity in adapting to harsh climates and environments.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] Historically, the defining characteristic of Alaska Native groups has often been their languages, which belong to several major language families.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] Currently, Alaska Natives or Native Alaskans constitute more than 20% of Alaska's population.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] The vast majority of Alaska Natives are either Eskaleut or Na Dene.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] As of 2018, Alaska Natives constituted 15.4% of the overall Alaskan population.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] Earlier data from the Alaskan Natives Commission estimated approximately 86,000 Alaska Natives residing in Alaska in 1990, with an additional 17,000 living outside of the state.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] More recently, a 2013 study conducted by the Alaska Department of Labor and Workforce Development documented over 120,000 Alaska Native Individuals within Alaska.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] While a significant portion of the Alaska Native populations resides in smaller villages or remote regional hubs such as Nome, Dillingham, and Bethel, there has been a notable increase in the percentage living in urban areas.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] According to the 2010 census, 44% of Alaska Natives lived in urban areas, a rise from 38% recorded in the 2000 census.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] The pre-contact population of Alaska Natives, in year 1750, before first European settlement, is estimated as around 93,800 people.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] In 1870 the native population of Alaska was still estimated as 70,000 people.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] However, the census of 1880 found only 32,996 Native Alaskans.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] The population of Alaska Natives then further declined to 25,450 people in 1910 (of whom 25,328 lived in Alaska and 122 in the rest of the United States).
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] Since 1910 the population began rebounding, and it reached 168,826 people in year 2010.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] Of them 124,758 lived in Alaska and 44,068 in the rest of the United States.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] The modern history of Alaska Natives began in the eighteenth century with the initial contact between Alaskan First Nations and Russian explorers sailing from Siberia.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] Subsequently, in the nineteenth century, British and American traders, coming mostly from eastern settlements in North America, arrived in the region.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] In some areas of Alaska, the active presence of Christian missionaries did not occur until the twentieth century.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] Vitus Bering spotted Alaska during an expedition.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] Subsequently, in the 18th century, Alaska Natives encountered Russians, with the timing of this contact varying among different Native groups across Alaska.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] Arriving by ship from Siberia, in the mid-eighteenth century, Russians established trade with Alaska Natives, particularly in the Aleutian Islands.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] They founded settlements around their trading posts, which included Russian Orthodox missionaries.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] These missionaries were the first to translate Christian scripture into Native languages, such as Tlingit.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] The lasting impact of this period is evident in the 21st century with numerous Russian Orthodox Christian congregations in Alaska composed predominantly of Alaska Natives.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] The Sibero-Russian *promyshlenniki*, rather than engaging in hunting and harvesting marine life themselves, coerced the Aleuts into performing this labor, enserfing the Aleuts.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] As news for the fur trade spread, competition among Russian companies intensified.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] Catherine the Great, upon ascending to the throne in 1763, expressed goodwill towards the Aleuts and encouraged fair treatment.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] However, the increasing competition between trading companies, which eventually consolidated into larger and more powerful corporations, led to conflicts that worsened relations with the Indigenous populations.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] Over time, the situation became dire for the Aleuts and other Native Alaskan people affected by Russian contact.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] As the animal populations declined, the Aleuts, already dependent on the new barter economy driven by the fur trade with the Russians, faced increasing pressure to take greater risks in the dangerous waters of the North Pacific to hunt for more otter.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] The Shelikhov-Golikov Company, and later Russian-American Company developed as a monopoly, using skirmishes and systematic violence as tools for the colonial exploitation of the Indigenous peoples.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] When the Aleut revolted and won some victories, the Russians retaliated with deadly force, destroying their boats and hunting equipment, leaving them no means of survival.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] The most devastating impact on the Aleut population during the initial two generations of Russian contact (1741/1759-1781/1799 AD) was the introduction of new diseases from Eurasia.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] Approximately 80% of the Aleut population perished from these infectious diseases, to which they had no immunity, unlike Europeans among whom these diseases have been endemic for centuries.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] The Russian Tsarist government expanded into Indigenous territory in present-day Alaska for its own geopolitical reasons.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] It consumed natural resources of the territory during the trading years, and Russian Orthodoxy was evangelized.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] Their movement into these populated areas of Indigenous communities altered the demographic and natural landscape.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] Historians have suggested that the Russian-American Company exploited Indigenous peoples as a source of inexpensive labor.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] The Russian-American Company not only used Indigenous populations for labor during the fur trade, but also held some as hostages to acquire *iasak*.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] Iasak, a form of taxation imposed by the Russians, was a tribute in the form of otter pelts.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] It was a taxation method the Russians had previously found useful in their early encounter with Indigenous communities of Siberia during the Siberian fur trade.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] Beaver pelts were also customary to be given to fur traders upon first contact with various communities.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] The Russian-American Company used military force on Indigenous families, taking them hostage until male community members produced furs for them.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] Otter furs on Kodiak Island and Aleutian Islands enticed the Russians to start these taxations.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] Robbery and maltreatment in the form of corporal punishment and the withholding of food was also present upon the arrival of fur traders.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] Catherine the Great dissolved the giving of tribute in 1799, but her government initiated mandatory conscription of Indigenous men between the ages of 18 and 50 to become seal hunters strictly for the Russian American Company.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] This mandatory labor gave the Russian American Company an edge in competition with American and British fur traders.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] But the conscription separated men from their families and villages, thus altering and breaking down communities.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] With able-bodied men away on the hunt, villages were left with little protection as only women, children, and the elderly remained behind.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] In addition to changes that came with conscription, the spread of disease also altered the populations of Indigenous communities.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] Although records kept in the period were scarce, it has been said that 80% of the pre-contact population of the Aleut people were gone by 1800.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] The Alaska Native population was first recorded in the 1880 United States census, and it was estimated that the population had declined from 80,000 in 1741 to 33,000 due to disease.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] The population continued to decline until 1910 and it was not until 1947 that this number surpassed the 1880 figure.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] Relationships between Indigenous women and fur traders increased as Indigenous men were away from villages.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] This resulted in marriages and children that would come to be known as Creole peoples, children who were Indigenous and Russian.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] To reduce hostilities with Aleutian communities, it became policy for fur traders to enter into marriage with Indigenous women.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] The Creole population increased in the territory controlled by the Russian American Company.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] The growth of the Russian Orthodox Church was another important tactic in the colonization and conversion of Indigenous populations.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] Ioann Veniaminov, who later became Saint Innocent of Alaska, was an important missionary who carried out the Orthodox Church's agenda to Christianize Indigenous populations.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] The church encouraged Creole children to follow Russian Orthodox Christianity, while the Russian American Company provided them with an education.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] Many Orthodox missionaries, like Herman of Alaska, defended Natives from exploitation.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] Creole people were believed to have high levels of loyalty toward the Russian crown and Russian American Company.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] After completing their education, children were often sent to Russia, where they would study skills such as mapmaking, theology, and military intelligence.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] In the 1850s Russia lost much of its interest in Alaska.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] Alaska's abundance of natural resources, particularly gold, drew the interest of the United States.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] In 1867, the United States bought Alaska from Russia.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] This purchase happened without considering the opinions of the Native Alaskans, who were not regarded as citizens at the time.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] The land traditionally belonging to Alaska Natives was treated as "open land," allowing white settlers to claim it without providing any compensation or recognition to the Native people living there.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] The only educational opportunities available for Alaska Natives were in schools established by religious missionaries.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] Many white settlers failed to appreciate the complex and well-developed cultures that Alaska Natives had created to thrive in their challenging environment.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] Instead, they viewed them as inferior to European Americans, which aligned with white supremacist ideologies.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] The Klondike Gold Rush of 1896–1898 led to increased white settlement in Alaska and brought discriminatory practices against Indigenous peoples.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] American settlers imposed racial segregation and discriminatory laws similar to Jim Crow laws, which severely limited Alaska Natives' opportunities and cultural practices, effectively treating them as second-class citizens.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] This segregation manifested in various ways, including "whites only" signs that prevented natives from entering certain buildings.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] Educational discrimination was also prevalent.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] In an 1880 court case, a child was barred from attending school with Americans because his stepfather was native.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] Children of mixed heritage could only attend American schools if their families abandoned their native culture.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] Simultaneously, the U.S. government implemented policies to disrupt Alaska Native family structures.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] Federal records show that disrupting native family units was a deliberate part of Federal Indian policy aimed at assimilating Indigenous children.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] The Federal Indian Boarding School Initiative played a major role in creating intergenerational trauma by removing children from their native villages and placing them in off-reservation boarding schools alongside children from other tribes.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] This system created artificial communities of Indigenous children throughout the boarding school network, resulting in new Indigenous family structures depending on whether children returned to their native villages or settled elsewhere after completing their education.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] These policies prohibited Alaska Native children from speaking their native languages, wearing traditional clothing, associating with other natives, consuming traditional foods, or practicing their religions.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] The resulting family separation and cultural eradication caused significant intergenerational trauma.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] In 1912, the Alaska Native Brotherhood (ANB) was formed to help fight for citizenship rights.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] The Alaska Native Sisterhood (ANS) was created in 1915.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] Also in 1915, the Alaska Territorial legislature passed a law allowing Alaskan Natives the right to vote – but on the condition that they give up their cultural customs and traditions.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] The Indian Citizenship Act, passed in 1924, gave all Native Americans United States citizenship.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] ANB began to hold a great deal of political power in the 1920s.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] They protested the segregation of Alaska Natives in public areas and institutions, and also staged boycotts.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] Alberta Schenck (Inupiaq) staged a well-publicized protest against segregation in a movie theater in 1944.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] With the help of Elizabeth Peratrovich (Tlingit), the Alaska Equal Rights Act of 1945 was passed, ending segregation in Alaska.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] In 1942, during World War II, the United States forced evacuation of around nine hundred Aleuts from the Aleutian Islands.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] The idea was to remove the Aleuts from a potential combat zone during World War II for their own protection, but European Americans living in the same area were not forced to leave.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] The removal was handled so poorly that many Aleuts died after they were evacuated; the elderly and children had the highest mortality rates.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] Survivors returned to the islands to find their homes and possessions destroyed or looted.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] Civil rights activists such as Alberta Schenck Adams and Elizabeth Peratrovich protested discriminatory laws against Native Alaskans with what were effectively sit-ins and lobbying.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] The Alaska Equal Rights Act of 1945, the first anti-discrimination state law in the U.S., occurred as a result of these protests.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] It entitled all Alaskans to "full and equal enjoyment" of public areas and businesses, a ban on segregating signs, with discriminatory actions punishable by a $250 fine and up to 30 days in jail.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] Alaska became part of the United States in 1959 upon President Dwight D.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] Eisenhower recognizing Alaska as the 49th state.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] In 1971, with the support of Alaska Native leaders such as Emil Notti, Willie Hensley, and Byron Mallott, the U.S.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] Congress passed the Alaska Native Claims Settlement Act (ANCSA), which settled land and financial claims for lands and resources which the Alaska Natives had lost to European-Americans.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] It provided for the establishment of thirteen Alaska Native Regional Corporations to administer those claims.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] Similar to the separately defined status of the Canadian Inuit and First Nations in Canada, which are recognized as distinct peoples, in the United States, Alaska Natives or Native Alaskans are in some respects treated separately by the government from other Native Americans in the United States.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] This is in part related to their interactions with the U.S. government which occurred in a different historical period than its interactions during the period of westward expansion during the 19th century.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] Europeans and Americans did not have sustained encounters with the Alaska Natives until the late 19th and early 20th centuries when many were attracted to the region in gold rushes.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] The Alaska Natives were not allotted individual title in severalty to land under the Dawes Act of 1887 but were instead treated under the Alaska Native Allotment Act of 1906.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] The Allotment Act was repealed in 1971, following ANSCA, at which time reservations were ended.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] Another characteristic difference is that Alaska Native tribal governments do not have the power to collect taxes for business transacted on tribal land, per the United States Supreme Court decision in *Alaska v.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] Native Village of Venetie Tribal Government* (1998).
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] Except for the Tsimshian, Alaska Natives no longer hold reservations but do control some lands.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] Under the Marine Mammal Protection Act of 1972, Alaska Natives reserve the right to harvest whales and other marine mammals.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] Four Indigenous tribes in Alaska, the Shishmaref, Kivalina, Shaktoolik, and Newtok tribes, are among America's first climate refugees due to the impacts of sea ice melting and increased wildfires in their regions.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] Climate change has created extensive challenges for Alaska's native peoples, including increased vulnerability to disease, mental health issues, physical injuries, and food and water insecurity.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] According to the Environmental Protection Agency (EPA), coastal erosion from sea ice loss is displacing native communities.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] This melting also disrupts the migration patterns of animals that tribes depend on for sustenance, while eliminating traditional places to store harvested food.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] As permafrost thaws, existing infrastructure becomes unstable, leading to the collapse of Native villages.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] The Shishmaref, Kivalina, Shaktoolik, and Newtok tribes are situated on Alaska's west coast, where rising sea levels have intensified storm surges that erode their coastlines.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] These communities face forced migration because there is no suitable nearby land to relocate to, requiring them to abandon their traditional ways of life.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] Predictions indicate that a significant climate event could completely submerge these tribal lands in fewer than fifteen years.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] The changing climate has heightened safety risks for Alaska Natives.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] While thick ice layers were historically present year-round, warming temperatures have thinned the ice, increasing incidents of people falling through—a dangerous situation that leads to additional health concerns even for survivors.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] Water insecurity and deteriorating infrastructure have created sanitation problems, contributing to an increase in respiratory illnesses across Alaska.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] In 2005, pneumonia became the leading cause of hospitalizations in these regions.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] Many affected communities experience significant psychological stress due to both the immediate impacts of climate change and the complex challenges of relocation without established policies or pathways.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] Additional stress comes from infrastructure damage caused by thawing permafrost, with minimal regulatory guidance beyond the Alaskan government's recommendations to avoid building on permafrost or to use extra insulation on foundation walls.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] Food security has also deteriorated as animals relocate to more suitable habitats.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] Traditional underground ice cellars, once frozen year-round, now thaw during summer months, rendering food supplies inedible.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] Gathering of subsistence food continues to be an important economic and cultural activity for many Alaska Natives.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] In Utqiaġvik, Alaska, in 2005, more than 91 percent of the Iñupiat households which were interviewed still participated in the local subsistence economy, compared with the approximately 33 percent of non-Iñupiat households who used wild resources obtained from hunting, fishing, or gathering.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] But, unlike many tribes in the contiguous United States, Alaska Natives do not have treaties with the United States that protect their subsistence rights, except for the right to harvest whales and other marine mammals.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alaska-natives] The Alaska Native Claims Settlement Act explicitly extinguished aboriginal hunting and fishing rights in the state of Alaska.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alligator-hunting] There is no single method of alligator hunting.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alligator-hunting] The use of a hook and line is the most common method.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alligator-hunting] It involves securing a sturdy hook and line to a tree or pole in the ground.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alligator-hunting] The hook is commonly baited with fish or chicken quarter.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alligator-hunting] After the bait is taken, the hunter returns to draw in and dispatch the gator.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alligator-hunting] Allowed methods of hunting vary by state, in South Carolina an alligator must be captured before being killed with either a handgun or bangstick.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alligator-hunting] A bangstick is a specialized underwater firearm fired only when in direct contact with the target.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alligator-hunting] Historically, unregulated hunting has led to dramatic decreases in alligator populations.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alligator-hunting] In 1973 the American alligator was listed as endangered under the Endangered Species Act of 1973.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alligator-hunting] The American alligator was listed as an endangered species in 1967 under a law that was a precursor to the Endangered Species Act of 1973.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alligator-hunting] Since the species' recovery, alligator hunting programs have been established in the majority of U.S. states in the alligator's habitat range.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alligator-hunting] The main products of alligator hunting are alligator meat and skin.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alligator-hunting] Alligator skins have been harvested since the 1800s.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alligator-hunting] Alligator skin was used in the manufacture of boots, belts, and saddles.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alligator-hunting] In the early 1900s some states began the commercial tanning of alligator skin.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alligator-hunting] The increased popularity of alligator leather led to the rise of alligator farming, now a $60 million industry.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alligator-hunting] Following the global economic recession of 2008, demand for wild alligator skins declined dramatically.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/alligator-hunting] In the state of Louisiana the number of reported skins dropped from 35,625 to 9,139 in one year.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/ambergris] Ambergris has been highly valued by perfume makers as a fixative that allows the scent to last much longer, although it has been mostly replaced by synthetic ambroxide.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/ambergris] Dogs are attracted to the smell of ambergris and are sometimes used by ambergris searchers.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/ambergris] The English word *amber* derives from Middle Persian ʾmbl, traveling via Arabic *ʿanbar* (عنبر), Middle Latin *ambar*, and Middle French *ambre* to be adopted in Middle English in the 14th century.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/ambergris] The word "ambergris" comes from the Old French *ambre gris* or "grey amber".
[src:aboriginal-whaling/ambergris] The addition of "grey" came about when, in the Romance languages, the sense of the word "amber" was extended to Baltic amber (fossil resin), as white or yellow amber (*ambre jaune*), from as early as the late 13th century.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/ambergris] This fossilised resin subsequently became the dominant (and now exclusive) sense of "amber", leaving "ambergris" as the word for the whale secretion.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/ambergris] The archaic alternate spelling "ambergrease" arose as an eggcorn from the phonetic pronunciation of "ambergris", encouraged by the substance's waxy texture.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/ambergris] Ambergris is formed from a secretion of the bile duct in the intestines of the sperm whale, and can be found floating on the sea or washed up on coastlines.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/ambergris] It is sometimes found in the abdomens of dead sperm whales.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/ambergris] Because the beaks of giant squids have been discovered within lumps of ambergris, scientists have suggested that the substance is produced by the whale's gastrointestinal tract to ease the passage of hard, sharp objects that it may have eaten.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/ambergris] It is speculated that an ambergris mass too large to be passed through the intestines is expelled via the mouth, but this remains under debate.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/ambergris] Another theory states that an ambergris mass is formed when the colon of a whale is enlarged by a blockage from intestinal worms and cephalopod parts resulting in the death of the whale and the mass being excreted into the sea.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/ambergris] Christopher Kemp, the author of *Floating Gold: A Natural (and Unnatural) History of Ambergris*, says that it is only produced by sperm whales, and only by an estimated one percent of them.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/ambergris] Ambergris is rare; once expelled by a whale, it often floats for years before making landfall.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/ambergris] The slim chances of finding ambergris and the legal ambiguity involved led perfume makers away from ambergris, and led chemists to find viable alternatives.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/ambergris] Ambergris is found primarily in the Atlantic Ocean and on the coasts of South Africa; Brazil; Madagascar; the East Indies; The Maldives; China; Japan; India; Australia; New Zealand; and the Molucca Islands.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/ambergris] Most commercially collected ambergris comes from the Bahamas in the Atlantic, particularly New Providence.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/ambergris] In 2021, fishermen found a 127 kg (280-pound) piece of ambergris off the coast of Yemen, valued at US$1.5 million.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/ambergris] Fossilised ambergris from 1.75 million years ago has also been found.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/ambergris] Ambergris is found in lumps of various shapes and sizes, usually weighing from 15 grams (1⁄2 ounce) to 50 kilograms (110 pounds) or more.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/ambergris] When initially expelled by or removed from the whale, the fatty precursor of ambergris is pale white in colour (sometimes streaked with black), soft, with a strong faecal smell.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/ambergris] Following months to years of photodegradation and oxidation in the ocean, this precursor gradually hardens, developing a dark grey or black colour, a crusty and waxy texture, and a peculiar odour that is at once sweet, earthy, marine, and animalic.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/ambergris] Its scent has been generally described as a vastly richer and smoother version of isopropanol without its stinging harshness.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/ambergris] In this developed condition, ambergris has a specific gravity ranging from 0.780 to 0.926 (meaning it floats in water).
[src:aboriginal-whaling/ambergris] It melts at about 62 °C (144 °F) to a fatty, yellow resinous liquid; and at 100 °C (212 °F) it is volatilised into a white vapour.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/ambergris] It is soluble in ether, and in volatile and fixed oils.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/ambergris] Ambergris is relatively nonreactive to acid.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/ambergris] White crystals of a terpenoid known as ambrein, discovered by Leopold Ružička and Fernand Lardon in 1946, can be separated from ambergris by heating raw ambergris in alcohol, then allowing the resulting solution to cool.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/ambergris] Breakdown of the relatively scentless ambrein through oxidation produces ambroxide and ambrinol, the main odour components of ambergris.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/ambergris] Ambroxide is now produced synthetically and used extensively in the perfume industry.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/ambergris] Ambergris has been mostly known for its use in creating perfume and fragrance much like musk.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/ambergris] Perfumes based on ambergris still exist.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/ambergris] The aroma is described as (characteristically) ambergris, animal, marine, seashore.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/ambergris] Ambergris has historically been used in food and drink.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/ambergris] A serving of eggs and ambergris was reportedly King Charles II of England's favourite dish.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/ambergris] A recipe for Rum Shrub liqueur from the mid 19th century called for a thread of ambergris to be added to rum, almonds, cloves, cassia, and the peel of oranges in making a cocktail from *The English and Australian Cookery Book*.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/ambergris] It has been used as a flavouring agent in Turkish coffee and in hot chocolate in 18th century Europe.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/ambergris] The substance is considered an aphrodisiac in some cultures.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/ambergris] Ancient Egyptians burned ambergris as incense, while in modern Egypt ambergris is used for scenting cigarettes.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/ambergris] Use as an incense can be seen in the John Singer Sargent painting Fumée d'Ambre Gris, painted in Tangiers and Paris in 1880.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/ambergris] The ancient Chinese called the substance "dragon's spittle fragrance".
[src:aboriginal-whaling/ambergris] During the Black Death in Europe, people believed that carrying a ball of ambergris could help prevent them from contracting plague.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/ambergris] This was because the fragrance covered the smell of the air which was believed to be a cause of plague.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/ambergris] During the Middle Ages, Europeans used ambergris as a medication for headaches, colds, epilepsy, and other ailments.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/ambergris] In New Zealand, ambergris found washed up on the shores was used by Māori as chewing gum in pre-colonial times.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/ambergris] From the 18th to the mid-19th century, the whaling industry prospered.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/ambergris] By some reports, nearly 50,000 whales, including sperm whales, were killed each year.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/ambergris] Throughout the 19th century, "millions of whales were killed for their oil, whalebone, and ambergris" to fuel profits, and they soon became endangered as a species as a result.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/ambergris] Because studies showed that the whale populations were being threatened, the International Whaling Commission instituted a moratorium on commercial whaling in 1982.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/ambergris] Although ambergris is not harvested from whales, many countries also ban the trade of ambergris as part of the more general ban on the hunting and exploitation of whales.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/ambergris] Urine, faeces, and ambergris (that has been naturally excreted by a sperm whale) are waste products not considered parts or derivatives of a CITES species and are therefore not covered by the provisions of the convention.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/ambrein] It has been shown to act as an analgesic and has been proven to increase sexual behavior in rats, providing some support for its traditional aphrodisiac use.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/ambrein] Apart from its supposed aphrodisiac effects, ambrein has been shown to decrease spontaneous contractions of smooth muscles in rats, guinea pigs, and rabbits.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/ambrein] It reduces these contractions by serving as an antagonist and interfering with Ca2+ ions from outside the cell.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/ambrein] The aroma is described as (characteristically) ambergris, labdanum, amber, woody.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/ambrein] In 1946, Ruzicka and Lardon "established that the fragrance of ambergris is based on the triterpene (named) ambrein".
[src:aboriginal-whaling/ambrein] Ambrein is synthesized from the common triterpenoid precursor squalene.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/ambrein] The squalene-hopene cyclase (SHC) catalyzes the cyclization of squalene into the monocyclic 3-deoxyachilleol A.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/ambrein] Tetraprenyl-beta-curcumene synthase (BmeTC) converts 3-deoxyachilleol A into the tricyclic ambrein.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Anti-whaling activism has a short history compared to other forms of activism and environmental awareness.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Early members of environmental organizations began protesting whale hunts around the world in the 20th century.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] These actions were in direct response to the global depletion of whale populations due to over-exploitation by the whaling industry and the failure of international whaling regulations.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] The League of Nations raised concerns about the over-exploitation of whale stocks and called for conservation measures in 1925.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] This eventually led to the Geneva Convention for the Regulation of Whaling which was presented in 1931 but did not enter into force until 1934 and was completely ignored by Germany and Japan.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] In 1937 the International Conference on Whaling added limits on pelagic whaling in order to prevent excessive exploitation (and specifically the extinction of the blue whale), thereby creating the International Agreement for the Regulation of Whaling.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] The International Convention for the Regulation of Whaling was created in 1946 in Washington to "provide for the proper conservation of whale stocks and thus make possible the orderly development of the whaling industry".
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Based on the previous 1937 Agreement and subsequent protocols to that agreement in 1938 and 1945, the ICRW led to the 1949 creation of the International Whaling Commission along with guidelines for the international regulation of coastal and pelagic whaling.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Critics charge that the IWC and ICRW have largely failed due to a lack of enforceable rules and regulatory loopholes.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] In 1966 the Convention on Fishing and Conservation of Living Resources of the High Seas took the first steps in marine conservation worldwide.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] This international treaty was designed to specifically counter the over-exploitation of sealife including whales.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] In 1972, the United Nations Conference on the Human Environment produced a 52–0 vote in favor of a 10-year global moratorium on commercial whaling.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] However, the UN resolution was not adopted by the IWC.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Iceland, Japan, Norway, Panama, Russia and South Africa voted no.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] In 1973, a moratorium was once again proposed and voted down in the IWC lacking the required 3/4 majority.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Iceland, Japan, Norway, Russia and South Africa voted no.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Between 1973 and 1982 the IWC would see its membership increase from 14 countries to 37.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] In 1972 the United States passed the Marine Mammal Protection Act as the first article of legislation to call specifically for an ecosystem approach to natural resource management and conservation.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] The act prohibits the hunting and killing of marine mammals, and enacts a moratorium on the import, export, and sale of any marine mammal, along with any marine mammal part or product within the United States.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] That same year the United States also enacted the Marine Protection, Research and Sanctuaries Act which established the National Marine Sanctuaries program.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] The United States would later play a significant role in the acceptance of a global moratorium on commercial whaling due to its domestic laws.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] In particular the 1971 Pelly Amendment to the US Fishermen's Protection Act gives the US President legal authority to prohibit importation of fish products from any nation that is diminishing the effectiveness of fisheries conservation programs.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] It was later strengthened by the 1979 Packwood-Magnuson Amendment to the Fishery Conservation and Management Act giving additional sanctioning power with regard to the ICRW.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Popular culture grew to widely accept whales and dolphins as interesting, entertaining and intelligent over the latter half of the 20th century.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] From the original tourist attractions at Marineland to giant SeaWorld theme parks, captive dolphins and orcas (killer whales) became star attractions.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] The 1960s television series *Flipper* starred a Lassie-like dolphin character who befriends a young boy and performs feats of intelligence often saving the day.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] The 1967 novel *The Day of the Dolphin*, which inspired the 1973 film, featured dolphins trained to speak English that help to save the world from nuclear destruction.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] In 1970 the biologist and environmentalist Roger Payne recorded and produced the popular *Songs of the Humpback Whale* album, after his 1967 discovery (with Scott McVay) of whale song among Humpback whales.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] With the growing popularity of entertaining cetaceans came information and even warnings about the threats to these adored animals.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] In 1966, Scott McVay first revealed the plight of whales to the public in his article "The Last of the Great Whales", for *Scientific American* and two years later "Can Leviathan Long Endure So Wide a Chase?" in *Natural History*.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Joan McIntyre (who later went on to found Project Jonah in 1972) both celebrated the whale and condemned the whaler in the 1974 publication *Mind in the Waters*.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] In 1975, *Audubon* dedicated an entire issue to whales titled "Vanishing Giants".
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] From 1968 to 1976 *The UnderSeaWorld of Jacques Cousteau* included film of whales, dolphins and other marine mammals as subjects of educational television.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] In 1977, *National Geographic* aired "The Great Whales" with scenes of whales being killed.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Before long, the words "Save the Whales" began to appear on bumper stickers, fliers, T-shirts and petitions.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Conservation groups dedicated to this purpose formed including both average citizens and social radicals whose ideas on how to respond varied widely.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] The first was the American Cetacean Society which was formed in 1971 and quickly followed by the Whale Center and Connecticut Cetacean Society.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Well established environmental organizations like the World Wildlife Fund, the National Wildlife Federation, the Humane Society of the United States, the Sierra Club and the National Audubon Society also joined the movement.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] The environmental organization Greenpeace formed in the early 1970s as an offshoot of the Sierra Club.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] In 1975 Greenpeace launched its first anti-whaling campaign by actively confronting Soviet whaling fleets in the North Pacific.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Two years later a splinter group of Greenpeace members formed the Sea Shepherd Conservation Society to protect sea life specifically using radical methods of direct action.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] The environmental group Greenpeace pioneered anti-whaling activism in the form of direct action.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Paul Spong, a New Zealand scientist who once studied the intelligence of orcas and friend of Canadian author Farley Mowat, helped convince then Greenpeace director, Robert Hunter, that the organization should confront Russian whalers in the Pacific.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Spong, under the guise of a scientist studying sperm whales, gained vital information on the coordinates of whaling fleets from the Bureau of Whaling Statistics in Norway.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] With this information, Greenpeace sailed out aboard the *Phyllis Cormack*, named for the wife of its original owner.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] On June 27, 1975, members of Canadian Greenpeace took the first ever direct action against whalers who were actively whaling near the Mendocino Ridge about 40 miles west of California.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] The Greenpeace activists navigated small inflatable Zodiac boats between the Russian whalers of the *Dalniy Vostok* fleet and the hunted whales.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] The tactic was intended to prevent the whaling ship gunner from firing the harpoon cannon due to the risk of accidentally striking and harming one of the activists.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] However, the Russian catcher ship *Vlastny* fired directly over the heads of Robert Hunter and activist Paul Watson.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] The event was filmed by Greenpeace and later broadcast in the United States by the CBS Evening News with Walter Cronkite and other major television networks.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] The activists were unable to stop the Russian whalers but the airing of this event on television was significant in raising public awareness by making the *Save the Whales* movement front-page news for the first time.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] In mid-July 1976, the Canadian Greenpeace deployed a newly acquired ship, an ex-minesweeper called the *James Bay*, to confront the *Dalniy Vostok* factory ship and its catcher fleet once again.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] The activists found the Russian whalers midway between California and Hawaii.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] However, this time the whalers did not fire their harpoon cannons.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Instead, the Russian fleet retreated and Greenpeace chased the whalers for two days and nights before being forced to return to Hawaii for refueling.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] After replenishing their fuel and supplies, the activists found and disrupted the Russian fleet again and chased the whalers northward as far as their fuel permitted.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] At the end of July 1977, the *James Bay* once again found Russian whalers in the Pacific.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] This time the factory ship *Vladivostok*, sister ship of the *Vostok*, and its catcher fleet was confronted about 700 miles off the coast of California.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] The activists filmed whalers at work and documented the Russians taking undersized whales.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] The human barrier tactic was used again but the whalers fired over the activists.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] A newly formed Hawaii based Greenpeace organization joined in the Pacific campaign against Russian whalers with a fast former sub-chaser called the *Ohana Kai*.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] The activists found the *Vostok* fleet 1,000 miles north of Hawaii.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] With her superior speed, the *Ohana Kai* chased the *Vostok* which ceased whaling during the pursuit.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] After a week, a team of activists boarded the *Vostok* with anti-whaling propaganda for the crew.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] At end of the summer the *Vladivostok* ceased whaling for another week, while it was followed by the *James Bay*, and was also boarded by the activists.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] French activist, Jean-Paul Fortom-Gouin, was impressed with the Greenpeace actions in the North Pacific and decided on a more aggressive approach.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Fortom-Gouin financed the operation and dubbed his group, which included Greenpeace's Robert Hunter, the Whale and Dolphin Coalition (Fortom-Gouin had also largely financed the Greenpeace-Hawaii action against Russian whalers).
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] He had previously worked with the Australian Project Jonah while serving as Panama's official representative to the IWC meeting in Canberra just two months prior.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] The effort to intervene against whaling in Australia did not go smoothly.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] In town, a gang of bikers called "God's Garbage", whose members also happened to be employed butchering whales, harassed the demonstrators.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] The activist group had not managed to arrange for a large mother-ship to support their Zodiacs as they chased whalers tens of miles out into shark filled waters in small inflatable boats carrying loads of excess fuel.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] The whaling company even brought the media out on its own boats after several days of prepping the reporters and explaining the benefits of whaling.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] When the activists attempted to get between the whalers and their targets the gunners fired over the Zodiacs resulting in several close calls for their crews.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] In the end, the action did not save a single whale.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] However, thanks to Project Jonah's long term lobbying and educational efforts, Australian public opinion against whaling was estimated to be about 70 percent.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] In fact, Phoebe Fraser, the young daughter of the Prime Minister Malcolm Fraser, wore a "Save the Whale" badge during the election campaign.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] The Prime Minister appointed an independent inquiry which recommended in 1978 that Australia outlaw whaling, ban all production and import of whale products and change its policies to oppose whaling domestically and internationally.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Australia became an anti-whaling nation.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] A non-government observer at the IWC took an interest in the unseen whaling operations conducted by private interests outside of the regulatory body.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Through an international network of contacts and with financial assistance from environmental organizations, Nick Carter traced documents of insurance, ownership, billing, import and export and more.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] His determined research uncovered evidence of unregulated whaling on a massive scale that environmentalists refer to as "pirate whaling".
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] One pirate whaler in particular came to represent the worst of the unregulated whaling industry.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Carter's evidence exposed the MV *Sierra* as a diesel powered hybrid catcher-factory ship hunting throughout the Atlantic in violation of many national laws, and completely without regard for international whaling regulations.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] *Sierra* was whaling illegally in areas forbidden by the IWC, prosecuted in the Bahamas and South Africa, forbidden entry to British controlled ports, and more.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] She harpooned critically endangered species, undersized whales, mothers and nursing calves, regardless of season, without license and without reporting her actions.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] The design of the ship itself, a catcher-factory hybrid complete with freezers to preserve the meat, enabled *Sierra* to operate in a cost-effective manner without a large fleet that would draw attention.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] In October, 1975, Carter released his investigative report to IWC commissioners and observers as well as international news media.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] The Norwegian bank, Forrentningsbanken, was exposed as the owner which prompted an immediate change to Beacon-Sierra Ltd..
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Japan's Taiyo Fishing Company was implicated with copies of a contract with *Sierra* for meat production, photos and names of Japanese crew aboard *Sierra*, and photos of cargo falsely labeled "Fresh Frozen Whale Meat.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Produce of Spain" transferred to a Japanese cargo ship.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Nick Carter was officially recognized by the United Nations Environment Program (UNEP) for his investigative role in exposing pirate whaling as well as other illicit trade in wildlife after his death in 2000.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] He was previously awarded the Goldman Prize in 1997 and highly regarded in his home country and internationally among conservationists.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] However, in the 1970s pirate whaling continued despite the public exposure and *Sierra* would not be stopped until a fateful confrontation with another anti-whaling activist named Paul Watson.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Allen Thornton, a Canadian activist, traveled to England in 1976 to establish a European Greenpeace presence.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] His fund raising efforts drew generous donations from comedian Spike Milligan and the Beatles.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] In 1977, he helped establish Greenpeace-UK.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] The new office was followed by additional Greenpeace offices in France, the Netherlands, Germany and Denmark.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Greenpeace activist, David McTaggart, assumed overall leadership of Greenpeace International.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] With the contributions in Europe and a grant from the World Wildlife Fund, the Greenpeace ship, *Rainbow Warrior*, was deployed in 1978 to confront Iceland's whalers in the North Atlantic.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] In the 1978 campaign, the *Rainbow Warrior* spent a month interfering with whaling operations in Icelandic waters without incident.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] In the 1986 Hvalur sinkings, activists from the Sea Shepherd Conservation Society sank two unoccupied whaling vessels, *Hvalur 6* and *Hvalur 7*, and sabotaged a whale processing station in Hvalfjörður.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] After splitting from Greenpeace, activist Paul Watson, with funding and support from Cleveland Amory (founder of The Fund for Animals), acquired a 779-ton deep-water trawler and renamed the ship, the *Sea Shepherd*.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] The bow of the ship was reinforced with many tons of concrete and set out for the North Atlantic to confront the infamous pirate whaler, *Sierra*.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Craig Van Note, of the Monitor Consortium (a group of conservation organizations based in Washington), provided Watson with vital information on the location of the *Sierra* from a global network of sources.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] On July 15, 1979, the *Sea Shepherd* found the *Sierra* near Oporto, Portugal and chased the whaler to the port of Leixoes.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] *Sierra* pretended to enter the port as if to dock and avoid further confrontation.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] However, as the *Sea Shepherd* entered the port the *Sierra* turned and fled leaving Watson to deal with the Portuguese harbor pilots who boarded the ship to guide her in, and the harbor officials who planned to detain the activist vessel.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Fourteen members of the crew were unwilling to continue and Watson left them ashore taking the *Sea Shepherd* out with a crew of three after the *Sierra*.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] When Watson caught up with the *Sierra* he put the concrete reinforced bow to work and rammed the pirate whaler.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] The first strike landed at the bow of the *Sierra* in a failed attempt to knock out the harpoon gun.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] For the second and final blow, the *Sea Shepherd* rammed the *Sierra* amidships leaving a large gash in the pirate whaler's hull.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Despite the damage, *Sierra* was able to limp back to Leixoes but hundreds of thousands of dollars and months of repairs would be needed to make the ship sea worthy again.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] *Sea Shepherd* attempted to escape but was quickly met by a Portuguese destroyer and escorted back to port.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Watson was briefly arrested and was threatened with the forfeiture of his ship by the decision of a Portuguese court.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] After several months of efforts to have the *Sea Shepherd* released, and with most of its valuable equipment stolen, Watson and engineer Peter Woof scuttled the ship to prevent her from falling into the whalers' hands.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] In February 1980, just as the *Sierra* was nearly completely repaired and refitted to continue whaling, unknown saboteurs hired by the Sea Shepherd Conservation Society used magnetic limpet mines to blow a hole in her side and sank the pirate whaler in Lisbon harbor, permanently ending her career.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] However, *Sierra* was hardly the world's only pirate whaling ship.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Nick Carter's continued efforts, in addition to investigations by Greenpeace and other groups, also uncovered pirate whalers in South America with an operation in Brazil labeled as a "Japanese whaling colony" by environmentalists.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] In Chile, a whaler operating in the service of a Panamanian front company conducted coastal whaling.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] In Peru, three pirate whalers were hunting year-round.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Elsewhere, in Taiwan four pirate whaling ships were taking whales from the South China Sea and others out of Korea were at work in the Sea of Japan.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] In each case, links to Japanese companies (particularly Taiyo Gyogyo) were discovered.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] In April 1979, Colin Eglin, leader of the South African opposition, urged the government to investigate pirate whaling while Andrew Behr (owner of the *Sierra* and other pirate whalers) now denied any links to such activities.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] However, at the same time two Panamanian flagged whaling ships, *Susan* and *Theresa* (each named for Behr's daughters), were being converted into hybrid factory-catcher ships just like the *Sierra* by a South African shipbuilder.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] A *Cape Times* reporter, Stephen Wrottesley, also discovered the Sierra Fishing Company was hiring a new crew in the Cape Town area and another ship, the MV *Fisher* (formerly the MV *Yashima Maru*), was also being refitted for whaling and was registered in Panama.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Nick Carter, his colleague Nan Rice, and many other conservationists personally urged Colin Eglin to act while international environmental organizations pressured the government for an official inquiry.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] When port authorities ordered all South African nationals off of the *Fisher*, a foreign crew took the ship to the Canary Islands and it was renamed the *Astrid*.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Soon after, the Sea Shepherd Conservation Society distributed wanted posters advertising a $25,000 reward to anyone who would sink it.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Andrew Behr relocated himself and his family to England and the *Susan* and *Theresa* were seized as a result of the inquiry.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] The legal battle to have the ships released failed and years later the two pirate whalers were used for target practice and destroyed by the South African Navy.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Industria Ballenera SA (IBSA) was Spain's only remaining whaling company which had operated with government support and without the restrictions of international regulations as Spain was not a member of the IWC.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] However, as a result of the *Sierra* scandal and increasing pressure from the US, Japan officially banned the import of whale meat from non-IWC members on July 5, 1979.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Predictably, Spain joined the IWC at the start of its next annual meeting and continued to ship whale meat to Japan.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] In December 1979, two explosions were heard in the port of Corcubión (Galicia, Spain) but the whaling ships there were not damaged.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Then on April 27, 1980, the whalers *Ibsa I* and *Ibsa II* were sunk in the port of Marin by unknown saboteurs hired by the Sea Shepherd Conservation Society with limpet mines in a manner similar to the sinking of the *Sierra*.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Later on June 17, 1980, Greenpeace activists aboard the *Rainbow Warrior* confronted the whaling ship, *Ibsa III*, again deploying zodiacs to maneuver between the whalers and the whales.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] After a few hours of interference, warships from the Spanish Navy arrived to pursue and eventually board the Greenpeace ship.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] The activist crew was formally arrested and the *Rainbow Warrior* confiscated despite claims that the incident took place in international waters.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Charged in a military court, the captain of the *Rainbow Warrior*, Jonathan Castle, refused to pay the $142,000 fine (1,200,000 pesetas) and the ship was held in the military harbor O Ferrol.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Spanish authorities disabled the activist vessel by removing the thrust block from its engine.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] However, for five months Greenpeace members kept the ship otherwise seaworthy while a secret effort was made to find a new thrust block.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] A replacement part was found, smuggled into Spain, and walked past the Spanish guards by Greenpeace members laughing and acting as if returning from a bout of drinking.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Finally, on November 8 the *Rainbow Warrior* escaped under cover of darkness during a changing of the guard.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] The Spanish Navy was unable (or unwilling) to find and recapture the activists who were given a heroes' welcome in Jersey on November 11 by cheering crowds.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Later, on November 15, the ship finally arrived to Amsterdam, her base.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] In 1981, the Spanish Socialist Workers Party sponsored a motion long supported by organized environmental lobbying to compel Spain's IWC delegates to vote for a moratorium and immediate halt to whaling.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] The motion passed on December 16 of the same year with an overwhelming majority.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] In 1979 the influence of environmentalists was realized in the membership of the International Whaling Commission through the nation of Seychelles.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Sidney Holt, a well known marine biologist and former IWC scientific committee member (one of the "Three Wise Men"), envisioned an ocean refuge for whales.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Holt's companion, Lyall Watson, a respected nature writer in Seychelles, put him in contact with the nation's president, Albert Rene.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] The tiny island country joined the IWC and Holt watched from an NGO observer's seat as Lyall Watson led the Seychelles delegation to propose and succeed in establishing an Indian Ocean whale sanctuary.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] However, the environmental victory did not come without cost.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Japan responded in 1980 by ending a grant scheme to Seychelles for a fisheries research and training vessel.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] A letter from the Japanese ambassador explained this grant would not be extended to the tiny island nation due to its position in the International Whaling Commission and stated this decision would be reversed if the attitude of the Seychelles government changed at the IWC.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Surprisingly, Maxine Ferrari, the Seychelles Minister of Development and Planning, quickly rejected and condemned Japan's actions.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] 25*, a Japanese fishing boat, was seized while fishing in Seychelles waters and fined $115,000.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] In April, 1982, Japanese Prime Minister Zenko Suzuki offered a $40 million aid package to Seychelles which was ultimately rejected as well.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] The Soviets reasoned that the best way to conduct a subsistence hunt was to employ a single modern whaling ship, the *Zevezdny*, to catch whales on behalf of the Siberian native people.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Instead of the average 10 to 30 whales historically claimed in one year, after 1955 the quota rose to nearly 200 gray whales and international observers were not permitted.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] On August 9, 1981, Paul Watson led a new crew, aboard the *Sea Shepherd II*, from Nome, Alaska into the territorial waters of the Soviet Union.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] When the activists arrived at the Soviet whaling station village of Loren they quickly discovered that the whaling operation had been dedicated to producing feed for a commercial mink farm, complete with non-aboriginal blonde haired, blue eyed Russian workers.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] They managed to film and photograph the whaling station.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] The evidence was later turned over to Congress.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] The activists were soon running from the Russian military, including helicopter gunships and a destroyer, but managed to escape into American waters.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] On July 18, 1983, Greenpeace made its own incursion into Siberia during the week of the annual IWC conference.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Greenpeace also landed at the whaling station at Loren.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] However, the Russians were not going to be caught off guard again.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Soldiers and police arrested the seven that made it ashore.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] The *Rainbow Warrior* was also chased by warships and helicopters and after a six-hour ordeal safely returned to the US.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] The Greenpeace activists were held captive for several days before a transfer was arranged with an American delegation led by Nome, Alaska Mayor, Leo Rasmussen.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] On the US-Russian border in the Bering Strait, the *Rainbow Warrior* peacefully met Russian warships to retrieve its crew.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Rasmussen gave the Soviets an "I Love Nome" button and returned with the activists aboard a Greenpeace zodiac.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] In January 1979, a Greenpeace investigator, Campbell Plowden, narrowly avoided arrest by the Chilean DINA (secret police) as he gathered information, including photographic evidence, on the whaling operation in San Vicente, Chile|.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] In 1981, two more Greenpeace activists covertly researched Chilean coastal whaling.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] They found a fleet of three outdated whaling ships that were only able to land 77 whales in 1976 but increased the quota to 500 in 1978.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Greenpeace discovered Japan's investment in Chilean whaling included a hybrid catcher-factory ship originally named the *Orient Maru No.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] 2*, then renamed the *Paulmy Star III*, and in 1980 it became the *Juan 9*.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Although it was prohibited to sell whaling equipment to non-members, export documents revealed the whaling ship was falsely listed as a shrimp trawler before Chile joined the IWC.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] The whalers consistently violated IWC regulations including hunting out of season and killing protected species.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] In 1984, the propeller shaft of the *Juan 9* broke resulting in financial troubles that led creditors to seize the ship the next year.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] In 1979 and 1980, Greenpeace activists gathered evidence of pirate whaling operations in the South China Sea and uncovered a regional unregulated whale meat trade implicating Taiwan, South Korea, and Japan.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Taiwan officials denied the existence of the pirate whalers, and Japan denied importing whale meat from Taiwan.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] However, the investigators discovered four (formerly Japanese) whaling ships (*Sea Bird*, *Sea Flower*, *Chi Hsin*, *Chu Feng*) with Taiwanese crews, Japanese officers, and Panamanian flags.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] The investigation continued in Japan's Tsukiji market where Campbell Plowden and Rebecca Clark found whale meat, packed by Marine Enterprises Co.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Ltd (a South Korean front company), that had originally come from Taiwan.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] In 1979, Japan reported the import of 1,800 tons of whale meat from South Korea, but the Koreans had only reported the export of 400 tons.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] This led Plowden and Clark to the Marine Enterprises processing plant to gather proof of Taiwan provided whale meat repackaged as a product of Korea for shipment to Japan.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] In late February 1980, just days after these findings were reported to the United States government, Japanese customs agents seized 300 tons of Korean whale meat as illegally imported from Taiwan.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] The Taiwanese government responded to the threat of sanctions from the US and to the loss of Japan's support by impounding the pirate whaling ships.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] In February 1978, an endangered blue whale washed ashore near the town of Conchan, Peru and died from massive harpoon wounds as Peruvian conservationist, Felipe Benavides watched.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] A Peruvian subsidiary of Japan's Taiyo Fisheries, known as Victoria del Mar, operated three coastal whaling ships (*Victoria* 1, 2, and 7) with a shore station in Paita.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] In 1982, Greenpeace sent in the *Rainbow Warrior*.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] On the December 13, several Greenpeace activists boarded the *Victoria 7* and chained themselves to the harpoon cannon.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] A day later, Peruvian marines cut the chains and arrested the protesters.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] The Greenpeace activists were threatened with charges of piracy.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] However, many Peruvians protested on their behalf including Felipe Benavides, who had opposed whaling for nearly 30 years.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] After several days, the activists were released with a $3,000 fine, and two weeks later, the *Rainbow Warrior* was released as well.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Despite continued protest and international diplomatic pressure, Peru continued whaling until 1986.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] After growing pressure from member nations, in 1979, the IWC established the Indian Ocean Whale Sanctuary as a practical conservation measure.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Three years later, in 1982, the IWC adopted a moratorium on commercial whaling, which took effect in 1986 and allowed for scientific research whaling.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] When Japan resumed whale hunts under the auspices of a research program, some anti-whaling countries and organizations criticized the moratorium's loophole for continued commercial whaling.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] On March 31, 2014, the International Court of Justice ruled that Japan must stop its whaling in the Antarctic.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] In 1994, the IWC created the Southern Ocean Whale Sanctuary in Antarctica to protect whales in their breeding grounds.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Two additional sanctuaries were proposed in 1998 by anti-whaling nations, but they failed to get enough votes in the IWC.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Throughout the past decade , while pro- and anti-whaling nations debated and deliberated at the IWC, private activists have organized a range of protests against commercial whaling.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Most notably, Greenpeace and Sea Shepherd Conservation Society continue separate campaigns of direct action against whale hunts conducted by Norway, Iceland, and Japan.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Both also conduct media campaigns and other public outreach to raise awareness.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Each organization criticizes the other for differing activist philosophies and each, in turn, receives criticism from both pro- and anti-whaling countries.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Tensions have grown over the past few years during Sea Shepherd's confrontations with Japanese whaling vessels in the whale sanctuary off the coast of Antarctica.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] In 2008, the documentary-style TV series *Whale Wars* began filming these confrontations, bringing some light to both sides of the controversy.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] The same year, two Greenpeace protesters were arrested in Japan for their investigation of whale meat.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] More recently , the Australian government, as an anti-whaling member of the IWC, set a November 2010 deadline to stop Japanese whaling in the Southern Ocean or face an international legal challenge.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] However, the IWC's ban on commercial whaling is under debate and could be overturned by the end of 2010.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] In a compromise aimed at ending a deadlock between anti-whaling nations and whaling countries, such as Norway, Iceland, and Japan, the IWC would permit limited commercial hunting.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] The IWC proposal drew immediate criticism from environmentalists, who described it as "disaster for whales".
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] There has been some resistance to subsistence hunting by the Sea Shepherd group.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] When the Makah people tried to revive their traditional hunt it was disrupted by Sea Shepherd's "chase boats".
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Greenpeace took a different position in stating that cultural revival of whaling by groups like the Makah is not the problem.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Greenpeace opposes all commercial whaling, claiming that it is not sustainable.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] However, they state that they do not oppose subsistence whaling by indigenous peoples.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] They promote whale watching as an alternative economic activity to commercial whaling.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] The following organizations have taken part in or supported anti-whaling activities.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Anti-whaling action is a part of both environmental activism and marine conservation.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Forms of expression may include but are not limited to protest as demonstration and direct action, outreach through media, and political maneuvering.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Often the most visible expression of anti-whaling activism is through public demonstration of protest: nonviolent action by groups of people, ranging from simple display of public signage and banners to picketing, walking in a march, or meeting (rally) to hear speakers.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Actions such as blockades and sit-ins may also be referred to as demonstrations, although these would normally be considered direct action.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Direct action is activity undertaken by individuals, groups, or governments to achieve anti-whaling goals outside of normal social/political channels: nonviolent and violent activities which target persons, groups, or property deemed to be engaged in whaling, commercial or otherwise.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Examples of nonviolent direct action include strikes, blockades, workplace occupations, sit-ins, and graffiti.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Violent direct actions include sabotage, vandalism, and assault.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Direct actions are sometimes a form of civil disobedience, but some (such as strikes) do not always violate criminal law.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] While protest often leads to publicity of anti-whaling activities, there are more direct ways to raise public awareness.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Media activism uses media and communication technologies for social movement, and/or tries to change policies relating to media and communication.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Websites, newsletters, calls to action, pamphlets, books, speaking tours, rallies and mass mailings are all examples of outreach efforts.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] Other more formal ways of affecting change are political campaigning, diplomacy, negotiation and arbitration, and lobbying are methods of influencing decisions made by the government (in groups or individually).
[src:aboriginal-whaling/anti-whaling] This includes all attempts to influence legislators and officials, whether by other legislators, constituents, or organized groups.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/arctic-journal] Since at least March 2018, a fake journal pretending to be the real *Arctic* has set up a website.
[src:aboriginal-whaling/arctic-journal] The real journal is hosted through the University of Calgary.
